article.description: Christi Thomas had 24 points and Alexis Kendrick added 16 to lead No. 16 Georgia over No. 14 Arkansas, 69-60, in an SEC matchup.
article.headline: Georgia doesn't give in to depleted roster, Arkansas
article.linkText: Georgia holds off Arkansas to end two-game skid
article.story:
ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- None of Georgia's women's basketball
players are old enough to remember when the 1987 Georgia men's team
advanced to the NCAA Tournament, but that did not prevent coach
Andy Landers from borrowing some magic from the past.

	   The 1987 men's team lost three of its top six players to
injuries and academics and played the last half of the season with
just eight players. When the school hoisted a banner on the wall to
honor the team's accomplishments, coach Hugh Durham ordered it
silver rather than the standard red and etched the initials TMW
along the bottom -- The Miracle Workers.

	   That was ancient history to the Lady Dogs until pregame Sunday
against Arkansas (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP), when Landers presented his eight players
with gray T-shirts reading "TMW'' on the chest and "Special'' on
the back.

	   Georgia (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) worked some magic in the second half Sunday, holding off
surging Arkansas for a 69-60 win to stop a two-game losing streak.

	   Christi Thomas scored 24 points for the Lady Dogs (18-7, 9-3
Southeastern Conference), and Alexis Kendrick hit six straight free
throws in the last 57 seconds.

	   "Coach told us that the 1987 men's team went to the Final Four,
and they only had about seven players,'' said Kendrick, who
finished with 16 points and five assists. "All they had was each
other.''

	   Kendrick was a little mixed up on her history since the 1987
team lost in the first round of the NCAA Tournament, but she got
the point.

	   The Lady Dogs are down to eight players, after a knee injury to
Ebony Felder in December and the suspension this week of leading
scorer Kara Braxton.

	   Arkansas (19-8, 6-6 SEC) lost its third straight, all against
ranked teams, despite 17 points from India Lewis and 16 from Dana
Cherry. The Lady Razorbacks, who have been outrebounded by an
average of five per conference game, outrebounded Georgia 21-12 in
the first half.

	   Arkansas led by as much as nine in the first half, 34-25, but
was up only 36-33 at halftime.

	   "We finally started rebounding the ball,'' said Mary Beth
Lycett, who led Georgia with eight. "Before that we were doing a
good job defensively, but they were getting so many offensive
rebounds.''

	   "It was a matter of necessity,'' said Kendrick. "We had to do
it to win the game.''

	   The reversal of rebounding paid off early in the second half
when Georgia went on a 16-0 run over a six-minute stretch, building
to a 51-40 lead with 9:43 to play. The Lady Bulldogs led by 10 with
4:32 to go when Arkansas mounted a comeback.

	   Lewis climaxed an 11-2 run with a 3-pointer with 1:03 to play to
cut the lead to one, 61-60. On the ensuing inbounds play, Kendrick
was fouled. Georgia's Lycett went to the line at first and made a
shot while the Arkansas bench was loudly protesting that Lycett had
inbounded the ball and hadn't been fouled.

	   Lycett's point was waved off, and Kendrick replaced her, hitting
both shots. On consecutive possessions, Arkansas missed and fouled
Kendrick, and she continued to make the shots.

	   "I think she likes being in that situation,'' said Landers.
"Arkansas had really turned up its defense, and we were having
trouble executing, so I was glad when it got to must-foul
situations.''

	   "There is not a freshman point guard in our league that is
better,'' praised Arkansas coach Gary Blair.

	   "A loss is never a positive thing,'' but that is the best we
have played since we played LSU,'' Blair said. "We made some big
shots down the stretch, and defensively I thought we played solid
the whole ball game.''
